WEBVTT

00:06.000 --> 00:12.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:15.111 --> 00:16.838
Is that all you got?

00:19.088 --> 00:22.395
I was hoping to trade these
for some coffee beans.

00:23.815 --> 00:25.355
You hungry?

00:25.465 --> 00:26.723
Yeah.

00:27.259 --> 00:28.738
Get some water.

00:28.824 --> 00:30.391
I'll make lunch.

00:49.473 --> 00:51.059
You know what to do, son.

00:51.188 --> 00:52.512
Yes, sir.

00:52.598 --> 00:54.191
Remember...

00:54.735 --> 00:56.215
this is our land.

00:56.523 --> 00:58.245
It's kill or be killed.

01:07.779 --> 01:09.543
<i>Mr. Schwieger. State Police.</i>

01:09.667 --> 01:11.082
<i>I need you to step outside.</i>

01:11.168 --> 01:12.309
Now.

01:18.981 --> 01:20.891
Kill or be killed.

01:22.821 --> 01:23.857
So where are we going?

01:23.942 --> 01:25.293
What are we doing?

01:25.378 --> 01:27.656
And who is this wonder of
wonders I just have to meet?

01:27.742 --> 01:29.833
What did you call him?
A walking anachronism?

01:29.962 --> 01:32.320
Lucas Schwieger, 16.

01:32.406 --> 01:33.961
He never attended school.

01:34.141 --> 01:36.450
He lives a completely
sheltered existence

01:36.535 --> 01:39.102
in a cabin with no
electricity or running water

01:39.211 --> 01:41.274
in the woods above
Sullivan County.

01:41.414 --> 01:43.022
His father, whom
he lived with,

01:43.107 --> 01:45.625
described himself as
a radical survivalist.

01:45.766 --> 01:48.375
He was, as far as I can tell,
the only person

01:48.460 --> 01:50.377
that Lucas had any
sustained contact with

01:50.462 --> 01:52.446
during his 16
years of life.

01:52.635 --> 01:53.726
Wow.

01:53.820 --> 01:55.868
A caseworker with
Child Protective Services

01:56.066 --> 01:59.539
heard about him, grew concerned,
came to pay him a visit...

01:59.775 --> 02:02.399
escorted by
the New York State Police.

02:02.720 --> 02:05.348
"Father and son opened fire,
killing the caseworker

02:05.433 --> 02:07.698
"and wounding
the State Police officer,

02:07.783 --> 02:10.720
who fired back,
killing the father."

02:11.165 --> 02:14.053
Ballistics indicate that while
Lucas shot the police officer,

02:14.138 --> 02:17.118
wounding him in the leg,
he didn't actually kill anyone.

02:17.205 --> 02:19.024
It was the father's gun
that did that.

02:19.148 --> 02:21.680
Nonetheless, he's being charged
as an adult for murder

02:21.766 --> 02:23.337
as part of a joint venture.

02:23.517 --> 02:26.579
Does he even understand
what's going on? The charges?

02:26.715 --> 02:29.068
That they want him
to stand trial?

02:29.153 --> 02:30.977
They want to punish him
for what happened?

02:31.063 --> 02:33.201
He didn't even understand
what an attorney was

02:33.287 --> 02:34.938
until I explained it to him.

02:35.055 --> 02:36.970
You know, it's not like
he's mentally impaired.

02:37.056 --> 02:38.947
In fact, in the little time
I've spent with him,

02:39.033 --> 02:40.558
he seems innately intelligent.

02:40.644 --> 02:42.213
But his only understanding
of the world

02:42.299 --> 02:44.141
is what's been taught
to him by his father.

02:44.227 --> 02:46.085
Well, obviously,
some doctor, somewhere,

02:46.170 --> 02:47.626
deemed him fit
to stand trial.

02:47.720 --> 02:49.970
You should also know
that Lucas did speak

02:50.056 --> 02:51.930
to the police
on the record.

02:52.176 --> 02:54.180
He already admitted
he shot the officer.

02:54.265 --> 02:55.766
Expressed clear intent.

02:55.852 --> 02:58.332
Insisted he would
do it again.

03:18.885 --> 03:20.452
He's a friend.

03:24.596 --> 03:26.299
My name's Dr. Jason Bull.

03:26.384 --> 03:27.996
Dr. Statton wanted me
to meet you.

03:28.081 --> 03:29.401
See if I could help you.

03:29.869 --> 03:31.330
Doctor, huh?

03:31.973 --> 03:33.213
I'm not sick.

03:33.330 --> 03:35.854
No. I'm not the doctor
that helps sick people.

03:35.949 --> 03:39.073
I'm the doctor that helps people
when they get into trouble,

03:39.463 --> 03:41.190
when they have to go to court.

03:42.095 --> 03:43.307
Do you know what court is?

03:43.393 --> 03:46.135
Did Dr. Statton explain
about court to you?

03:50.321 --> 03:51.893
Let me start over.

03:53.367 --> 03:57.371
First of all,
I'm sorry about your father.

03:58.720 --> 04:00.505
They had better guns.

04:03.549 --> 04:05.885
How about your mom?

04:06.807 --> 04:08.330
Do you ever see her?

04:08.509 --> 04:09.949
Is there any way
I could talk to her?

04:10.034 --> 04:11.244
No.

04:11.528 --> 04:13.053
She hung herself.

04:13.474 --> 04:15.041
It was when I was a little kid.

04:17.055 --> 04:18.538
I'm sorry.

04:24.982 --> 04:26.332
Lucas...

04:27.314 --> 04:29.318
do you understand
you could spend

04:29.403 --> 04:31.463
the rest of your life
in here, in jail?

04:31.986 --> 04:34.002
And I'm guessing you don't
want that. Am I right?

04:34.088 --> 04:35.151
I just want to go home.

04:35.237 --> 04:38.346
And that's what we want to try
and make happen.

04:39.413 --> 04:41.198
You all right
with that?

04:45.271 --> 04:46.604
I guess so.

04:47.510 --> 04:48.760
All right.

04:49.123 --> 04:52.389
Let me get back to my office,
get this started.

04:52.638 --> 04:54.893
I'm sure I'm gonna want
to talk to you some more.

04:54.979 --> 04:57.393
In the meantime, is there
anything I can bring you?

04:57.512 --> 05:00.733
Anything you miss?
Maybe some books?

05:06.355 --> 05:09.471
Well, if you think
of anything.

